{{Redirect|Torreira|the handball player|Devora Torreira}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Spanish name|Torreira|Di Pascua}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Lucas Torreira | image = Lucas Torreira (cropped).jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Torreira with [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] | fullname = Lucas Sebastián Torreira Di Pascua<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tournament.fifadata.com/documents/FWC/2018/pdf/FWC_2018_SQUADLISTS.PDF |title=FIFA World Cup Russia 2018: List of players: Uruguay |publisher=FIFA |format=PDF |page=32 |date=15 July 2018 |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1996|2|11|df=y}}<ref name=PremProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/23033/Lucas-Torreira/overview |title=Lucas Torreira: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Fray Bentos]], Uruguay | height = 1.68 m<ref name=PremProfile/> | position = [[Midfielder]] | currentclub = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] | clubnumber = 11 | youthyears1 = 2010–2013 | youthclubs1 = 18 de Julio | youthyears2 = 2013 | youthclubs2 = [[Montevideo Wanderers F.C.|Montevideo Wanderers]] | youthyears3 = 2013–2014 | youthclubs3 = [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]] | years1 = 2014–2015 | clubs1 = [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]] | caps1 = 5 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2015–2018 | clubs2 = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] | caps2 = 71 | goals2 = 4 | years3 = 2015–2016 | clubs3 = → [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara]] (loan) | caps3 = 29 | goals3 = 4 | years4 = 2018– | clubs4 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] | caps4 = 29 | goals4 = 2 | nationalyears1 = 2018– | nationalteam1 = [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] | nationalcaps1 = 13 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | pcupdate = 22:20, 2 March 2019 (UTC) | ntupdate = 08:27, 23 December 2018 (UTC) }} '''Lucas Sebastián Torreira Di Pascua''' ({{IPA-es|ˈlukas toˈreiɾa}}; born 11 February 1996) is a Uruguayan professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for {{English football updater|Arsenal}} club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and the [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay national team]].
==Club career== ===Early career=== Torreira started his youth football career at hometown club I.A. 18 de Julio of [[Fray Bentos]]. In 2013, he joined [[Montevideo Wanderers F.C.|Montevideo Wanderers']] youth team before moving to Italy where he joined [[Delfino Pescara 1936|Pescara's]] youth team.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}
===Pescara=== [[File:Lucas Torreira, militante del pescara.jpg|200px|thumb|Torreira playing for Pescara in 2014]]
Before the 2014–15 season, Torreira was called up for Pescara's first team and, on 25 October 2014, he sat on the bench for the first time. He made his senior debut in [[Serie B]] on 16 May 2015 against [[Varese Calcio S.S.D.|Varese]], playing the game as a starter. He played 58 minutes before being replaced with [[Matteo Politano]].
===Sampdoria=== On 1 July 2015, Torreira was transferred to [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] for €1.5 million, but he remained with Pescara on loan for the 2015–16 season to gain first-team experience.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/done-deal-sampdoria-sign-pescara-midfielder-lucas-torreira-4083811 |title=DONE DEAL: Sampdoria sign Pescara midfielder Lucas Torreira|date=1 July 2015|work=Tribal Football}}</ref>
====Pescara (loan)==== On 2 July, his loan to Pescara became official.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.sampdoria.it/en/torreira-out-to-earn-his-samp-stripes-im-here-for-the-long-haul/ |title=Torreira out to earn his Samp stripes: "I’m here for the long haul"|date=10 July 2016|publisher=U.C. Sampdoria}}</ref> On 9 August 2015, Torreira scored his first professional goal against [[F.C. Südtirol]] in the [[2015–16 Coppa Italia]].
====Return to Sampdoria==== After the Pescara loan ended, Torreira returned to [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] on 1 July 2016. On 21 August 2016, Torreira made his [[Serie A]] debut in their opening game against [[Empoli F.C.|Empoli]] at the [[Stadio Carlo Castellani]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sampdoria.it/en/match/serie-a-tim-20162017-empoli-sampdoria-2/|title=U.C. Sampdoria – Serie A TIM 2016/2017: Empoli – Sampdoria|publisher=U.C. Sampdoria |accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref> He started the game and played the entirety of the 90+ minutes on the field.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}
He became a regular for Sampdoria in the 2016–17 season, and continued showing his importance to the team in the 2017–18 season; scoring vital goals, including the second goal in Sampdoria's 3–2 win over Juventus in November.{{citation needed|date=August 2018}}
===Arsenal=== On 10 July 2018, Torreira joined English club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] for an undisclosed fee, believed to be around £26.4m.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44764063|title=Arsenal: Lucas Torreira agrees deal & Matteo Guendouzi set for medical|date=10 July 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Torreira was given the number 11 shirt, previously worn by [[Mesut Özil]], who took the vacant number 10 following the departure of [[Jack Wilshere]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/lucas-torreira-join-arsenal|title=Lucas Torreira to join Arsenal|publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref>
====2018–19 season==== Torreira made his Premier League debut on 12 August, coming on as a substitute on the 70th minute in a 2–0 defeat to Manchester City.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Arsenal 0–2 Manchester City: Raheem Sterling and Bernardo Silva give champions win | first = Emlyn | last = Begley | publisher = BBC Sport | date = 12 August 2018 | accessdate = 13 August 2018 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45073327}}</ref> Torreira registered his first assist of the season, by setting up [[Alexandre Lacazette]]'s winning goal in a 3–2 win over [[Cardiff City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45312124|title=Cardiff City 2-3 Arsenal|last=Pearlman|first=Michael|date=2 September 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Torreira made his full-debut and his [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] debut for Arsenal in the 4–2 win over [[FC Vorskla Poltava]] on 2 September, before being replaced in the 57th minute by [[Mattéo Guendouzi]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45577861|title=Arsenal 4-2 Vorskla Poltava|last=Sutcliffe|first=Steve|date=20 September 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Torreira's performance in Arsenal's 1–1 draw with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] drew particularly high praise from fans and pundits alike, picking up the man-of-the-match award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2018/nov/04/lucas-torreira-arsenal-new-grit-under-unai-emery-liverpool|title=Lucas Torreira, the Mighty Insect, embodies Arsenal’s new grit - Barney Ronay|first=Barney Ronay at the Emirates|last=Stadium|date=4 November 2018|work=The Guardian}}</ref> On 2 December, Torreira scored his first Arsenal goal and picked up another man-of-the-match award against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] when he latched on to a pass from [[Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang]] to slot the ball past [[Hugo Lloris]] to give Arsenal a fourth goal in a 4–2 [[North London derby]] victory. A week later, on 8 December, Torreira scored a late 83rd-minute winner against [[Huddersfield Town]] with a bicycle kick, giving him his second goal in as many games at the Emirates Stadium. In the match, Torreira was also awarded his fifth consecutive Arsenal Man of the Match performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46409328|title=Arsenal 1-0 Huddersfield Town|last=Skelton|first=Jack|date=8 December 2018|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Torreira was dismissed in stoppage time, during the club's reverse fixture against Tottenham at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]], after a late challenge on Tottenham, defender [[Danny Rose]], the match ended 1-1 and was Torreira's first red card for Arsenal.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47340485</ref>
==International career== Torreira was born in Uruguay, and is of Spanish descent through his paternal grandfather from [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.elobservador.com.uy/nota/la-increible-historia-de-esfuerzo-de-lucas-torreira-contada-por-su-padre-20187518490 |title=La increíble historia de esfuerzo de Lucas Torreira contada por su padre |trans-title= |work=El Observador |date=5 July 2018 |accessdate=4 February 2019 |language=es}}</ref> He holds a Spanish passport, and was scouted by the senior [[Italy national football team]] before he was capped by Uruguay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dev.spherasports.net/lucas-torreira-cinco-mas-completo-calcio-153091/|title=Lucas Torreira, el cinco más completo del Calcio |work=Sphera Sports|date=29 September 2017}}</ref>
Torreira was called up to full [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] squad for the [[2018 China Cup]] in March 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getfootballnewsitaly.com/2018/torreira-earns-first-uruguayan-call-up/|title=Torreira earns first Uruguayan call-up |work=Get Italian Football News}}</ref> He made his debut in the 2–0 win over the Czech Republic in the China Cup semi final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sampdoria.it/en/torreira-makes-uruguay-debut-china-cup-victory-czech-republic/|title=Torreira makes Uruguay debut in China Cup victory over Czech Republic |publisher=U.C. Sampdoria|date=23 March 2018}}</ref>
In May 2018, he was named in Uruguay's provisional 26 man [[Uruguay national football team|squad]] for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb|title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad - Final 23-man lists| work=Goal}}</ref>
==Style of play== Upon signing for Arsenal in 2018, ''[[The Independent]]'''s Jack Austin stated "Torreira is exactly the kind of no-nonsense midfielder the club have been craving", adding that in Uruguay colours during the 2018 World Cup "he went about his job as the [[Midfielder#Holding midfielder|deep-lying pivot]] in the middle of the park with none of the fuss and all of the discipline of a player who has built a tidy reputation for himself in Serie A", while assessing his chief weaknesses as a lack of height in aerial duels and little goal threat.<ref>{{cite news|title=Arsenal transfer news: This is what Lucas Torreira will bring to Unai Emery's midfield, World Cup 2018 scouting report|first=Jack|last=Austin|work=The Independent|date=10 July 2018|accessdate=12 July 2018|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/arsenal-transfer-news-lucas-torreira-who-profile-tactics-world-cup-2018-scouting-report-uruguay-a8440601.html}}</ref>
WhoScored notes that he is a player that likes to shoot from distance and often gets fouled. They also note that he likes to play short passes and make tackles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whoscored.com/Players/248109/Show/Lucas-Torreira|title=Lucas Torreira Football Statistics |website=WhoScored.com|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref>
==Career statistics== ===Club=== {{updated|match played 24 February 2019}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/players/lucas-torreia-di-pascua/348191/ |title=L. Torreira: Summary |website=Soccerway |publisher=Perform Group |accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref>
